{"question_id": 26, "hits": {"dense": {"11:2": 0.5962198376655579, "29:2": 0.5814073085784912, "27:4": 0.5724815130233765, "33:1": 0.5697163343429565, "30:1": 0.5528607368469238, "12:3": 0.5425330400466919, "12:2": 0.5272727012634277, "31:1": 0.5221091508865356}, "bm25": {"31:1": 13.21215744108507, "33:1": 12.939617284471515, "30:1": 12.839208031717915, "11:2": 11.206011311357795, "29:3": 10.706092670575272, "12:1": 10.48530736504283, "29:2": 10.441860732918533, "27:4": 10.273953765200885}}, "expanded": ["11:1", "11:2", "11:3", "12:1", "12:2", "12:3", "27:3", "27:4", "29:1", "29:2", "29:3", "30:1", "31:1", "33:1", "33:2"], "answer": "On the night of Ramchandra Ray's escape, Udayaditya was the dominant figure who commanded Sitaram to open the door, threatened him with a sword, and tied him up. This dynamic reversed during Udayaditya's own escape, where Sitaram became the orchestrator and rescuer who grabbed the helpless prince from his prison cell and led him to safety."}
{"question_id": 27, "hits": {"dense": {"2:1": 0.7369608879089355, "5:2": 0.6722160577774048, "10:3": 0.6397573351860046, "4:2": 0.6245993971824646, "5:1": 0.5941100120544434, "28:2": 0.5700711011886597, "33:4": 0.5687718391418457, "12:3": 0.5446782112121582}, "bm25": {"2:1": 13.68656285875944, "4:2": 11.759484538441537, "28:1": 10.584338391170139, "19:2": 10.208098705483671, "5:2": 9.645130467388094, "12:2": 9.056405459720663, "13:3": 8.41036619913485, "28:2": 8.376351610337558}}, "expanded": ["2:1", "2:2", "4:1", "4:2", "4:3", "5:1", "5:2", "5:3", "10:2", "10:3", "12:1", "12:2", "12:3", "13:2", "13:3", "19:1", "19:2", "19:3", "28:1", "28:2", "28:3", "33:3", "33:4"], "answer": "Pratapaditya's initial failed plan was to have two Pathan men kill Basanta Ray on the road while he was traveling to Jessore, specifically when he took shelter at the inn in Simultali. The method that finally succeeded was a signed order for Basanta Ray's death sentence, carried out by Muktiyar Khan's soldiers, who killed him with a sword."}
{"question_id": 28, "hits": {"dense": {"7:1": 0.5010293126106262, "24:3": 0.47127965092658997, "7:3": 0.46286365389823914, "24:2": 0.45014357566833496, "7:2": 0.44977831840515137, "9:2": 0.44289809465408325, "37:1": 0.430616557598114, "8:2": 0.42782753705978394}, "bm25": {"8:2": 17.412089419202815, "37:1": 15.229165633709885, "24:2": 14.46736605082906, "24:3": 13.994162911176963, "7:1": 13.612032711165734, "7:3": 13.39004497510312, "9:2": 12.747951280097219, "19:1": 12.468013758166052}}, "expanded": ["7:1", "7:2", "7:3", "8:1", "8:2", "8:3", "9:1", "9:2", "19:1", "19:2", "24:1", "24:2", "24:3", "37:1"], "answer": "Ramai Bhand faces physical retaliation from Rammohan Mal in the following two locations and disguises:\n1. In the inner quarters (specifically the Mahishi's room), while disguised as a middle-aged woman (Mother Nikasha).\n2. In the king's room, while as the jester."}
{"question_id": 29, "hits": {"dense": {"16:1": 0.6901664733886719, "21:3": 0.5490074753761292, "17:1": 0.545799195766449, "15:1": 0.5413951873779297, "13:1": 0.5386990308761597, "5:3": 0.5385221242904663, "1:3": 0.5281519889831543, "11:1": 0.5176244974136353}, "bm25": {"1:3": 13.135992936854787, "16:1": 10.761895751803408, "20:1": 10.159757638912035, "1:1": 8.865880333275314, "13:1": 8.66508239582274, "18:1": 8.577636217105354, "15:1": 8.247010924846576, "17:1": 7.690146156981089}}, "expanded": ["1:1", "1:2", "1:3", "5:2", "5:3", "11:1", "11:2", "13:1", "13:2", "15:1", "16:1", "17:1", "18:1", "20:1", "21:2", "21:3"], "answer": "Pratapaditya's threat to have Udayaditya imprisoned if Surma did not leave."}
{"question_id": 30, "hits": {"dense": {"36:2": 0.643839955329895, "37:1": 0.6282038688659668, "23:1": 0.6233672499656677, "24:1": 0.6128988265991211, "26:1": 0.6021869778633118, "36:1": 0.5920947790145874, "9:1": 0.5852378606796265, "36:3": 0.5848116874694824}, "bm25": {"19:3": 10.607967155214116, "9:1": 9.338258287582693, "7:3": 8.97191583722899, "6:1": 7.758074292445316, "23:1": 7.291371009714478, "9:2": 6.967519539695595, "36:3": 6.686608789047338, "10:3": 6.654658405171854}}, "expanded": ["6:1", "6:2", "7:2", "7:3", "9:1", "9:2", "10:2", "10:3", "19:2", "19:3", "23:1", "23:2", "24:1", "24:2", "26:1", "36:1", "36:2", "36:3", "37:1"], "answer": "Because Vibha refused to go with Rammohan Mal during his first attempt to escort her to Chandradwip, King Ramchandra Ray felt insulted and eventually married another woman. Consequently, when Vibha finally arrived at the palace, the King rejected her, denied that she was his Mahishi, and treated her as a beggar, leading her to spend the rest of her life in Kashi in charity, meditation, and caring for her brother."}
{"question_id": 31, "hits": {"dense": {"27:4": 0.510663628578186, "33:3": 0.48511433601379395, "12:3": 0.4698697328567505, "34:1": 0.4656837582588196, "29:2": 0.4612429440021515, "33:1": 0.4580061435699463, "23:2": 0.4550924301147461, "25:1": 0.45492273569107056}, "bm25": {"27:4": 13.079932856052254, "14:1": 6.095926261275164, "23:2": 5.684873088532121, "5:3": 5.442880802594518, "21:3": 5.2515314792297945, "18:1": 5.239737150708086, "37:1": 5.1628403118102675, "8:1": 5.022322192755088}}, "expanded": ["5:2", "5:3", "8:1", "8:2", "12:2", "12:3", "14:1", "18:1", "21:2", "21:3", "23:1", "23:2", "25:1", "27:3", "27:4", "29:1", "29:2", "29:3", "33:1", "33:2", "33:3", "33:4", "34:1", "37:1"], "answer": "Sitaram and Rukmini conspired in secret, with Sitaram stating that he needed Bhagavat's help to proceed, and Rukmini obtained the ring from Udayaditya; subsequently, Bhagavat presented a forged petition to Pratapaditya, which was used to justify Udayaditya's imprisonment."}
{"question_id": 32, "hits": {"dense": {"10:1": 0.49126696586608887, "11:1": 0.4766502380371094, "16:1": 0.46633216738700867, "17:1": 0.4599302411079407, "12:1": 0.45875945687294006, "9:2": 0.4442446827888489, "24:2": 0.4342457056045532, "11:4": 0.42723074555397034}, "bm25": {"11:1": 7.970582952532109, "19:1": 7.78797916912319, "1:3": 7.487115349519604, "10:1": 7.073896008464455, "11:4": 6.876841173032734, "10:2": 5.1186541781293355, "8:1": 4.986246736988717, "6:1": 4.903687534155235}}, "expanded": ["1:2", "1:3", "6:1", "6:2", "8:1", "8:2", "9:1", "9:2", "10:1", "10:2", "10:3", "11:1", "11:2", "11:3", "11:4", "12:1", "12:2", "16:1", "17:1", "19:1", "19:2", "24:1", "24:2", "24:3"], "answer": "The midnight escape of Ramchandra Ray required the guards of the inner quarters to be tied up, and to protect Udayaditya from the consequences, Basanta Ray paid the guard Bhagavat a secret stipend to lie and claim that Basanta Ray was the one who had tied them up. When word of these secret stipends reached Pratapaditya, he ordered that Surma be sent to her paternal home."}
{"question_id": 33, "hits": {"dense": {"27:2": 0.677990198135376, "13:3": 0.4594215154647827, "28:1": 0.44929900765419006, "27:3": 0.43697255849838257, "4:1": 0.4210028648376465, "13:2": 0.39376115798950195, "4:2": 0.3905285596847534, "13:1": 0.3660026490688324}, "bm25": {"27:2": 17.119467759285733, "27:3": 17.113134158908487, "13:3": 10.792812498923213, "28:1": 10.398817152197822, "4:1": 10.032412568463878, "13:2": 8.964630261162634, "35:1": 8.410244720192724, "33:1": 8.405953800297091}}, "expanded": ["4:1", "4:2", "4:3", "13:1", "13:2", "13:3", "27:1", "27:2", "27:3", "27:4", "28:1", "28:2", "33:1", "33:2", "35:1"], "answer": "The song 'I alone am left behind' signifies emptiness and the grief of losing loved ones who no longer answer his call or are present to listen to his music. Basanta Ray sings it in two contrasting contexts: first, in solitary reflection on the veranda of his palace in Raigarh while gazing at the setting sun, and second, in Jessore, upon discovering that Surma's room is empty and silent, while holding Vibha's hand."}
{"question_id": 34, "hits": {"dense": {"30:1": 0.5841017961502075, "4:2": 0.5546918511390686, "12:2": 0.543941855430603, "11:1": 0.5199499130249023, "33:3": 0.5187011361122131, "21:3": 0.5094279646873474, "13:1": 0.4832189083099365, "11:4": 0.4795137643814087}, "bm25": {"30:1": 11.281606018050967, "31:1": 10.198757974625181, "2:3": 7.983379914361043, "1:3": 7.616255157054182, "29:1": 7.451108046013147, "33:2": 7.428115049153639, "33:3": 7.152427246242231, "21:3": 7.053762527931214}}, "expanded": ["1:2", "1:3", "2:2", "2:3", "4:1", "4:2", "4:3", "11:1", "11:2", "11:3", "11:4", "12:1", "12:2", "12:3", "13:1", "13:2", "21:2", "21:3", "29:1", "29:2", "30:1", "31:1", "33:1", "33:2", "33:3", "33:4"], "answer": "Rukmini failed to stop Udayaditya as he was boarding the boat to escape with Basanta Ray. After the boat cast off, she informed King Pratapaditya that Udayaditya had escaped with the old king. In response, Pratapaditya sent Muktiyar Khan to Raigarh with a signed order for the death sentence of the King of Raigarh, which Muktiyar Khan then carried out by executing Basanta Ray."}
{"question_id": 35, "hits": {"dense": {"8:3": 0.6899212598800659, "8:2": 0.6758604645729065, "19:1": 0.6007470488548279, "19:2": 0.5862668752670288, "24:2": 0.5700105428695679, "12:1": 0.5677062273025513, "10:3": 0.5672070384025574, "5:2": 0.5493168234825134}, "bm25": {"19:1": 14.031360419137794, "19:2": 10.15800201728831, "24:2": 6.959692121656633, "9:2": 6.283527332249451, "26:1": 6.025482889910831, "12:2": 5.988533685334985, "28:1": 5.370212005110514, "12:3": 5.200765567844066}}, "expanded": ["5:1", "5:2", "5:3", "8:1", "8:2", "8:3", "9:1", "9:2", "10:2", "10:3", "12:1", "12:2", "12:3", "19:1", "19:2", "19:3", "24:1", "24:2", "24:3", "26:1", "28:1", "28:2"], "answer": "Pratapaditya's initial reception of Ramchandra Ray was cold and indifferent; he provided a poor welcome with no musical fanfare or lit paths, sent a small escort and a small elephant, and later ignored Ramchandra in his royal chamber to read a document, eventually dismissing him by telling him to go to the inner quarters. In contrast, Ramchandra later addresses Pratapaditya's status in his own court through daily ridicule and contempt, where his courtiers mock Pratapaditya's lineage by calling his grandfather an earthworm and his father a leech, claim Pratapaditya's father had to beg for royal anointment, and view the marriage connection as a favor that redeemed Pratapaditya's generations while lowering the status of Ramchandra's own home."}
{"question_id": 36, "hits": {"dense": {"33:1": 0.5246785879135132, "34:1": 0.5177992582321167, "1:2": 0.5127061009407043, "33:3": 0.49292922019958496, "21:3": 0.48640674352645874, "4:2": 0.47512930631637573, "30:1": 0.4727054238319397, "10:2": 0.4654494524002075}, "bm25": {"1:2": 12.453553976262398, "10:3": 11.445864014192718, "17:1": 8.72222399974643, "1:1": 7.965726697051944, "30:1": 7.738688884303084, "33:2": 6.795337535597174, "33:1": 6.6584588690276, "22:1": 6.4092289804799965}}, "expanded": ["1:1", "1:2", "1:3", "4:1", "4:2", "4:3", "10:1", "10:2", "10:3", "17:1", "21:2", "21:3", "22:1", "30:1", "33:1", "33:2", "33:3", "33:4", "34:1"], "answer": "Rukmini, the widow from Raigarh, re-enters Udayaditya's life by changing her name to Mangala and living on the outskirts of Jessore. She causes tragedy by providing a poison, disguised as medicine to win the Yubaraj's heart back from Surma, which leads to Surma's death. Later, she tricks Udayaditya into giving her a ring with his seal, which is used to create a forged petition of treason, resulting in Udayaditya's arrest and the execution of Basanta Ray."}
{"question_id": 37, "hits": {"dense": {"34:1": 0.6516848206520081, "1:1": 0.5717340707778931, "2:3": 0.5257581472396851, "33:1": 0.5134386420249939, "1:2": 0.5101281404495239, "15:1": 0.5003705024719238, "19:2": 0.4996567666530609, "21:3": 0.4941069483757019}, "bm25": {"1:1": 15.363280543146967, "2:3": 7.812006004469232, "34:1": 7.618580756888913, "23:1": 6.727642444028817, "19:2": 6.436626015151029, "29:2": 5.551551586152704, "12:3": 5.438235048909766, "17:1": 5.284415491300605}}, "expanded": ["1:1", "1:2", "1:3", "2:2", "2:3", "12:2", "12:3", "15:1", "17:1", "19:1", "19:2", "19:3", "21:2", "21:3", "23:1", "23:2", "29:1", "29:2", "29:3", "33:1", "33:2", "34:1"], "answer": "Udayaditya's early lament stems from his belief that he lacks the intellect for ruling, his failure to manage the Hosenkhali pargana, and the burden of his father's expectations and despise. This culminates when Udayaditya returns to Jessore as a prisoner and tells Pratapaditya that he is not worthy of the kingdom and does not want it. He formally renounces the throne by swearing an oath before Ma-Kali that he will never accept any part of the kingdom of Jessore, will not sit on the throne, and will not touch the royal scepter, naming Samaraditya as the heir."}
{"question_id": 38, "hits": {"dense": {"26:1": 0.6626584529876709, "28:4": 0.6259502172470093, "6:1": 0.6008896231651306, "24:1": 0.59980309009552, "9:2": 0.5906857252120972, "10:1": 0.5789715051651001, "19:2": 0.5613994002342224, "24:2": 0.5609039068222046}, "bm25": {"28:4": 8.319197845446435, "26:1": 8.221205084471395, "24:2": 6.705958261864004, "11:1": 6.091667422715177, "15:1": 5.969287924884624, "7:1": 5.925093664825849, "6:1": 5.604020457145353, "8:3": 5.311558994285329}}, "expanded": ["6:1", "6:2", "7:1", "7:2", "8:2", "8:3", "9:1", "9:2", "10:1", "10:2", "11:1", "11:2", "15:1", "19:1", "19:2", "19:3", "24:1", "24:2", "24:3", "26:1", "28:3", "28:4"], "answer": "Ramchandra Ray's letter, which stated that he had renounced Vibha and that she should not be sent to Chandradwip again, was given to the old Nayanchand. Fearing Pratapaditya's potential reaction, Nayanchand intercepted the letter and gave it to the Mahishi instead. After reading the letter, Basanta Ray advised the Mahishi to misrepresent its contents by announcing to the household that Ramchandra had written the letter to request that Vibha be sent to Chandradwip."}
{"question_id": 39, "hits": {"dense": {"12:1": 0.5406250357627869, "10:1": 0.5239338874816895, "11:4": 0.5149523615837097, "10:3": 0.4799426198005676, "19:2": 0.4727940857410431, "5:2": 0.4576225280761719, "11:1": 0.4566054940223694, "24:1": 0.456180214881897}, "bm25": {"12:1": 9.822093673415678, "11:1": 8.69781961977365, "10:1": 7.722814942472401, "2:3": 6.637090002126089, "11:4": 6.132970322328532, "19:2": 5.3924825581191405, "19:3": 5.309608709968499, "26:1": 5.297518113640492}}, "expanded": ["2:2", "2:3", "5:1", "5:2", "5:3", "10:1", "10:2", "10:3", "11:1", "11:2", "11:3", "11:4", "12:1", "12:2", "19:1", "19:2", "19:3", "24:1", "24:2", "26:1"], "answer": "Pratapaditya attempted to trap Ramchandra Ray by ordering the canal adjoining the royal palace, where Ramchandra's boat was located, to be blocked with large logs of Sal wood. This failed when Rammohan and his followers pulled the boat up and over the logs."}
{"question_id": 40, "hits": {"dense": {"4:2": 0.6564171314239502, "13:3": 0.6337608098983765, "27:4": 0.6305446624755859, "12:2": 0.6267789602279663, "33:1": 0.6112121939659119, "28:2": 0.5971034169197083, "27:2": 0.5899398922920227, "33:2": 0.5830053687095642}, "bm25": {"13:3": 9.471871468510532, "27:3": 9.027796569919625, "4:1": 8.687298020737861, "16:1": 7.963722899440848, "13:1": 7.45721723955664, "6:4": 7.35607729998898, "12:3": 7.12162787340432, "1:1": 6.884804391448595}}, "expanded": ["1:1", "1:2", "4:1", "4:2", "4:3", "6:3", "6:4", "12:1", "12:2", "12:3", "13:1", "13:2", "13:3", "16:1", "27:1", "27:2", "27:3", "27:4", "28:1", "28:2", "28:3", "33:1", "33:2", "33:3"], "answer": "Basanta Ray's relationship with his sitar evolves from viewing it as an \"eternal companion\" used to create merriment and joy to a symbol of his despair. During his farewell to Udayaditya, his playing becomes \"furiously\" clattered and \"greatly hindered\" by his tears, eventually leading him to put it down and declare, \"I am leaving this sitar behind, Dada, I will not play it anymore.\" Later, while reflecting on his loneliness and emptiness, he reveals that although he still has the sitar, its strings have broken and it \"can no longer be tuned.\""}
{"question_id": 41, "hits": {"dense": {"21:3": 0.5685317516326904, "1:2": 0.5538787841796875, "15:1": 0.5437471270561218, "20:1": 0.522802472114563, "16:1": 0.5219544172286987, "1:1": 0.5177510380744934, "17:1": 0.512856125831604, "5:3": 0.5066681504249573}, "bm25": {"13:3": 10.510358525608767, "16:1": 9.592064430884902, "6:2": 9.32882322380919, "20:1": 8.11983837454985, "1:2": 7.119218546916062, "18:1": 7.037504496985541, "8:1": 6.950520381724985, "1:1": 6.697904332414641}}, "expanded": ["1:1", "1:2", "1:3", "5:2", "5:3", "6:1", "6:2", "6:3", "8:1", "8:2", "13:2", "13:3", "15:1", "16:1", "17:1", "18:1", "20:1", "21:2", "21:3"], "answer": "Earlier, Udayaditya was beloved by his subjects, mixed with common people, and often opposed his father to take their side. He would provide them with advice and stop officials from abusing subjects without considering the consequences. After Surma's death, Udayaditya lost his courage and became extremely afraid of Pratapaditya. He no longer fought against oppression; for example, when he saw a royal official beating a subject, he ran into his house instead of intervening, and he abandoned a plan to stop the looting and burning of a zamindar's estate office. Additionally, he no longer had the courage to provide financial help to dismissed guards, either openly or secretly."}
{"question_id": 42, "hits": {"dense": {"22:1": 0.5544700622558594, "31:1": 0.4905102252960205, "15:1": 0.4625145494937897, "12:3": 0.4577699303627014, "27:1": 0.4513242542743683, "29:1": 0.40199515223503113, "21:2": 0.4018150568008423, "12:2": 0.39432793855667114}, "bm25": {"12:2": 11.88097102310579, "22:1": 9.073632276841549, "15:1": 8.403608116899784, "12:3": 6.8672141318606466, "11:2": 6.646094510871875, "31:1": 5.997974120711024, "21:2": 5.795228849178024, "37:1": 5.612158700634522}}, "expanded": ["11:1", "11:2", "11:3", "12:1", "12:2", "12:3", "15:1", "21:1", "21:2", "21:3", "22:1", "27:1", "27:2", "29:1", "29:2", "31:1", "37:1"], "answer": "Sitaram undoes the damage by orchestrating a fire at the prison with the help of palace servants and commoners. He uses the blaze as a cover to rescue Udayaditya from his cell and fakes the prince's death by throwing bones, a skull, and Udayaditya's sword into the burning ruins."}
{"question_id": 43, "hits": {"dense": {"11:3": 0.48710373044013977, "19:3": 0.47747641801834106, "11:2": 0.4305717349052429, "24:2": 0.42714011669158936, "7:3": 0.4172741770744324, "24:1": 0.40478280186653137, "9:1": 0.404336154460907, "9:2": 0.3987860381603241}, "bm25": {"8:2": 13.689206462796552, "13:1": 7.892127999957133, "1:1": 7.147388242887164, "7:3": 7.064555555922363, "23:1": 6.8419357126851015, "37:1": 6.529998582886377, "19:3": 6.440814883486574, "6:4": 6.209160752834251}}, "expanded": ["1:1", "1:2", "6:3", "6:4", "7:2", "7:3", "8:1", "8:2", "8:3", "9:1", "9:2", "11:1", "11:2", "11:3", "11:4", "13:1", "13:2", "19:2", "19:3", "23:1", "23:2", "24:1", "24:2", "24:3", "37:1"], "answer": "On the first occasion, Rammohan Mal ties several thick, large sheets together to create a rope, attaches it to a pillar on the palace roof, and carries King Ramchandra Ray on his back. He climbs down the rope and, upon reaching the end, grips the rope with his teeth to carefully lower the king into a boat before jumping down himself. On the second occasion, after Vibha faints from shame and insult, Rammohan lifts her, carries her out of the palace, and places her into a palanquin near the gate."}
{"question_id": 44, "hits": {"dense": {"36:3": 0.5989651679992676, "37:1": 0.5636138916015625, "6:1": 0.5434214472770691, "8:1": 0.5404127836227417, "9:1": 0.5184082984924316, "28:1": 0.5049175024032593, "6:2": 0.5033173561096191, "24:1": 0.5006279945373535}, "bm25": {"10:3": 12.52529240747297, "26:1": 10.525746539955609, "6:1": 10.278633614275908, "37:1": 9.529892878299265, "9:2": 8.95666414143369, "18:1": 8.195454350419245, "9:1": 7.7355879559826075, "28:4": 7.574950954257613}}, "expanded": ["6:1", "6:2", "6:3", "8:1", "8:2", "9:1", "9:2", "10:2", "10:3", "18:1", "24:1", "24:2", "26:1", "28:1", "28:2", "28:3", "28:4", "36:2", "36:3", "37:1"], "answer": "When preparing to receive Ramchandra Ray in Jessore, Vibha is dressed elaborately by the Mahishi in heavy royal adornments, including a large nose ring, eight thick gold bangles and one huge diamond bracelet on each arm, and a specific coiffure. In contrast, when she seeks him out in Chandradwip, she refuses a palanquin and dresses as a common woman and beggar-woman, entering the palace like a maidservant."}
{"question_id": 45, "hits": {"dense": {"21:3": 0.5225136280059814, "25:1": 0.513981819152832, "29:2": 0.48962080478668213, "1:2": 0.4799972176551819, "16:1": 0.4743289351463318, "1:1": 0.4702813923358917, "27:4": 0.4640476703643799, "18:1": 0.4626014828681946}, "bm25": {"20:1": 12.048155262308672, "25:1": 11.928834146245354, "31:1": 11.49109364931013, "18:1": 10.373265449062119, "16:1": 10.325420011756947, "17:1": 9.796801948584102, "21:3": 9.357367244195334, "29:2": 8.413330961651669}}, "expanded": ["1:1", "1:2", "1:3", "16:1", "17:1", "18:1", "20:1", "21:2", "21:3", "25:1", "27:3", "27:4", "29:1", "29:2", "29:3", "31:1"], "answer": "In his bedchamber after Surma's death, the window symbolizes longing and loss, as Udayaditya sits there reflecting on Surma's absence and the emptiness of the spot where she used to sit. In the prison cell, the window symbolizes hope and liberation; by looking at the sky and birds through it, Udayaditya feels \"naturally free\" and believes that his \"cage\" will one day break, allowing him to be released."}
{"question_id": 46, "hits": {"dense": {"21:1": 0.6063070893287659, "21:2": 0.5827865600585938, "27:1": 0.51873379945755, "31:1": 0.5165632367134094, "21:3": 0.45064204931259155, "17:1": 0.4265846312046051, "30:1": 0.42597320675849915, "14:1": 0.3602283000946045}, "bm25": {"21:2": 16.71225642095359, "21:1": 14.138151342095183, "31:1": 12.149549273825375, "30:1": 10.044257003664951, "17:1": 8.495168638167728, "11:2": 8.315118820258869, "15:1": 8.069929748693966, "4:1": 7.950699688028168}}, "expanded": ["4:1", "4:2", "11:1", "11:2", "11:3", "14:1", "15:1", "17:1", "21:1", "21:2", "21:3", "27:1", "27:2", "30:1", "31:1"], "answer": "The dynamic begins as a flirtatious financial arrangement where Sitaram, a stylish man in poverty, borrows money from Rukmini (Mangala), who lends money at interest. Sitaram is attracted to both Rukmini's beauty and her wealth, and the two engage in playful romantic banter, with Sitaram calling her terms of endearment such as \"Priyatame\" and \"Pranpriye\" while Rukmini feigns affection.\n\nThe relationship devolves when Sitaram discovers Udayaditya has been imprisoned; he visits Rukmini to curse and threaten her, vowing to free the Yubaraj. This triggers a possessive rage in Rukmini, who declares the Yubaraj is hers. The encounter becomes life-threatening during Udayaditya's escape, when Rukmini pounces on Sitaram to get to the prince, injuring Sitaram's shoulder. Later, when Sitaram enters Rukmini's cottage to steal her money, she threatens to lay him and the Yubaraj in an oven and attempts to attack him with a curved blade, forcing Sitaram to flee."}
{"question_id": 47, "hits": {"dense": {"31:1": 0.6055879592895508, "29:3": 0.5416193604469299, "29:2": 0.511566162109375, "27:4": 0.4670291244983673, "11:2": 0.46541717648506165, "12:3": 0.46133941411972046, "15:1": 0.4578703045845032, "21:3": 0.45739924907684326}, "bm25": {"31:1": 14.129963832509604, "27:1": 9.68820106801308, "29:2": 8.966902488151177, "30:1": 8.479378914885869, "29:3": 7.920777121672069, "36:1": 7.629444218410065, "33:1": 6.444203025256892, "27:4": 6.359523822072785}}, "expanded": ["11:1", "11:2", "11:3", "12:2", "12:3", "15:1", "21:2", "21:3", "27:1", "27:2", "27:3", "27:4", "29:1", "29:2", "29:3", "30:1", "31:1", "33:1", "33:2", "36:1", "36:2"], "answer": "Sitaram's strategy begins as a distraction when he orchestrates a fire in the guardhouse huts using loyal commoners and palace servants to create chaos and draw guards away, allowing him to lead Udayaditya out of his prison cell. To maintain this distraction, Sitaram's men sabotage firefighting efforts by breaking water pots and pouring water where there is no fire. The strategy evolves into a full-fledged cover-up after Udayaditya escapes by boat; Sitaram's men set fire to the empty prison cell, and Sitaram plants a skull, bones, and Udayaditya's sword inside. He then informs the guards that the roof has collapsed and Udayaditya is unresponsive, leading the palace to believe the Yubaraj died in the fire."}
{"question_id": 48, "hits": {"dense": {"19:2": 0.5781075954437256, "4:2": 0.5549581050872803, "12:2": 0.5456820130348206, "10:1": 0.5245153307914734, "12:3": 0.5209699869155884, "19:1": 0.5173285007476807, "24:2": 0.5142835378646851, "5:1": 0.5061213374137878}, "bm25": {"19:1": 10.284100698164677, "9:2": 9.002032723295143, "12:1": 7.858404950560942, "19:2": 7.554759532343823, "24:2": 7.41847812183283, "8:2": 7.311690207145119, "14:1": 7.311425661286758, "11:1": 7.25936814505505}}, "expanded": ["4:1", "4:2", "4:3", "5:1", "5:2", "8:1", "8:2", "8:3", "9:1", "9:2", "10:1", "10:2", "11:1", "11:2", "12:1", "12:2", "12:3", "14:1", "19:1", "19:2", "19:3", "24:1", "24:2", "24:3"], "answer": "Ramchandra Ray is not grateful for Udayaditya's actions, interpreting them as something that was bound to happen and would have been wrong if it had not. He believes that Udayaditya saved him for the sake of his own sister rather than making the saving of Ramchandra Ray's life the main objective."}
{"question_id": 49, "hits": {"dense": {"2:2": 0.610782265663147, "2:3": 0.6051692962646484, "8:3": 0.4949021637439728, "5:2": 0.484432190656662, "12:3": 0.47797611355781555, "12:1": 0.4577845633029938, "2:1": 0.453199565410614, "19:1": 0.4489462971687317}, "bm25": {"2:3": 17.635531351347435, "2:2": 14.472552366684402, "15:1": 8.556706241668111, "10:3": 8.24516339313427, "22:1": 7.6135423693011415, "14:1": 6.999333977915122, "18:1": 6.601333031508975, "12:3": 6.336593259423049}}, "expanded": ["2:1", "2:2", "2:3", "5:1", "5:2", "5:3", "8:2", "8:3", "10:2", "10:3", "12:1", "12:2", "12:3", "14:1", "15:1", "18:1", "19:1", "19:2", "22:1"], "answer": "Pratapaditya initially dismisses the Emperor of Delhi as a threat, calling the fear of him \"empty fears\" and finding it \"deeply insulting\" to be dissuaded by the Emperor's potential displeasure. However, the Emperor's political specter becomes the mechanism used against his son when Bhagavat and Sitaram create a forged petition, stamped with Udayaditya's seal, which falsely claims that Udayaditya is lodging a complaint of treason against Pratapaditya with the Emperor of Delhi in order to seize the kingdom for himself. Bhagavat delivers this forged petition to Pratapaditya."}
{"question_id": 50, "hits": {"dense": {"18:1": 0.6085778474807739, "8:1": 0.6030477285385132, "6:3": 0.5710793137550354, "6:1": 0.5532738566398621, "6:2": 0.5460044741630554, "17:1": 0.5353541374206543, "28:1": 0.5284503102302551, "16:1": 0.5003132820129395}, "bm25": {"8:1": 10.45388628892487, "17:1": 10.400172076039294, "18:1": 8.154428030899371, "6:3": 7.967023279275009, "6:1": 7.6077961769143085, "6:2": 7.412660278111085, "31:1": 7.352956472334547, "30:1": 7.13559418531943}}, "expanded": ["6:1", "6:2", "6:3", "6:4", "8:1", "8:2", "16:1", "17:1", "18:1", "28:1", "28:2", "30:1", "31:1"], "answer": "The grooming of Vibha's hair marks Surma's presence through acts of comfort and autonomy; Surma gently ran her fingers through Vibha's hair to soothe her distress and secretly styled it to Vibha's own liking to spare her from the Mahishi's unbearable coiffure. Surma's tragic absence is marked by Vibha sitting quietly and waiting for Surma to braid her hair, only for her hair to remain unbraided as she realizes Surma will not return."}
